<div class="story-body">
    <p>But much of Africa-China trade and diplomatic relationship has been defined by the latter’s investment in the former. From 2000 to 2017, the Chinese government, banks and contractors extended US $143 billion in loans to African governments and their state-owned enterprises (SOEs), according to CARI report. Angola is the top recipient of Chinese loans, with $42.8 billion disbursed over 17 years.</p>
    <p>Chinese President Xi Jinping, last year while opening Forum on China-Africa Cooperation (FOCAC), at Beijing’s Great Hall of the People, said China will invest more $60 billion in Africa. This will include $15 billion of aid, interest-free loans and concessional loans, a credit line of $20 billion, a $10 billion special fund for China-Africa development, and a $5 billion special fund for imports from Africa.</p>
    <p>Transport, power and mining top sectors where Chinese loans have been invested in Africa, according to a CARI data base.</p>


